        To compute Ax, first we multiply by C\inv to find the \cB-coordinates of x, then we multiply by B, then we multiply by C again.  For instance, let \textcolor{seq-green}x = {0\choose -2}.



            We see from the \cB-coordinate grid below that
            \textcolor{seq-green}x = -\textcolor{seq-violet}{v_1} + \textcolor{seq-blue}{v_2}.  Therefore, C\inv\textcolor{seq-green}x = \textcolor{seq-green}{[x]_\cB} = {-1\choose 1}.



            Multiplying by B scales the coordinates: \textcolor{seq-red}{B[x]_\cB} = {-2\choose -1}.



            Interpreting {-2\choose -1} as a \cB-coordinate vector, we multiply by C to get

              \textcolor{seq-red}{Ax} = C\vec{-2 -1} = -2\textcolor{seq-violet}{v_1} - \textcolor{seq-blue}{v_2} = \vec{-3 -1}.

            Of course, this vector lies at (-2, -1) on the \cB-coordinate grid.



\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.85, thin border nodes]
