\end{tikzpicture}

        Now let \textcolor{seq-green}x = \frac 12{5\choose -3}.



            We see from the \cB-coordinate grid that
            \textcolor{seq-green}x = \frac 12\textcolor{seq-violet}{v_1} + 2\textcolor{seq-blue}{v_2}.  Therefore, C\inv\textcolor{seq-green}x = \textcolor{seq-green}{[x]_\cB} = {1/2\choose 2}.



            Multiplying by B scales the coordinates: \textcolor{seq-red}{B[x]_\cB} = {1\choose -2}.



            Interpreting {1\choose -2} as a \cB-coordinate vector, we multiply by C to get

              \textcolor{seq-red}{Ax} = C\vec{1 -2} = \textcolor{seq-violet}{v_1} - 2\textcolor{seq-blue}{v_2} = \vec{-1 3}.

            This vector lies at (1, -2) on the \cB-coordinate grid.



