example.p:
        Consider the matrices

          A' = \frac 15\mat{-8 -9; 6 13} \qquad
          B = \mat{2 0; 0 -1} \qquad
          C' = \frac 12\mat{-1 -3; 2 1}.

        Then A' = C'B(C')\inv, as one can verify.  Let v_1'=\frac 12{-1\choose 2} and v_2' = \frac 12{-3\choose 1}, the columns of C', and let \cB' = \{v_1',v_2'\}.  Then A' does the same thing as B, as in the previous , except A' uses the \cB'-coordinate system.  In other words:



            B scales the e_1-direction by 2 and the e_2-direction by -1.



            A' scales the v_1'-direction by 2 and the v_2'-direction by -1.



