        Now let \textcolor{seq-green}x = \frac 12{-1\choose -2}.



            We see from the \cB-coordinate grid that
            \textcolor{seq-green}x = -\frac 12\textcolor{seq-violet}{v_1} - \textcolor{seq-blue}{v_2}.  Therefore, C\inv\textcolor{seq-green}x = \textcolor{seq-green}{[x]_\cB} = {-1/2\choose -1}.



            Multiplying by B rotates by 90^\circ: \textcolor{seq-red}{B[x]_\cB} = {1\choose -1/2}.



            Interpreting {1\choose -1/2} as a \cB-coordinate vector, we multiply by C to get

              \textcolor{seq-red}{Ax} = C\vec{1 -1/2} = \textcolor{seq-violet}{v_1} - \frac 12\textcolor{seq-blue}{v_2} = \frac 14\vec{9 3}.

            This vector lies at (1, -\frac 12) on the \cB-coordinate grid.



