note.p:
The converse of the  is false.  Indeed, the matrices
\mat{1 1; 0 1} \sptxt{and} \mat{1 0 ; 0 1}
both have characteristic polynomial f(\lambda) = (\lambda-1)^2, but they are not similar, because the only matrix that is similar to I_2 is I_2 itself.

statement.p:
Suppose that A = CBC\inv. Then
\begin{split} v \text{ is an eigenvector of } A \amp\quad\implies\quad C\inv v \text{ is an eigenvector of } B \\ v \text{ is an eigenvector of } B \amp\quad\implies\quad C v \text{ is an eigenvector of } A. \\ \end{split}
The eigenvalues of v / C\inv v or v / Cv are the same.

specialcase.p:
        We continue with the above : let

          A = \mat{1/2 3/2; 3/2 1/2} \qquad
          B = \mat{2 0; 0 -1} \qquad
          C = \mat{1 1; 1 -1},

        so A = CBC\inv.  Let v_1 = {1\choose 1} and v_2 = {1\choose -1}, the columns of C.  Recall that:



            B scales the e_1-direction by 2 and the e_2-direction by -1.



            A scales the v_1-direction by 2 and the v_2-direction by -1.


        This means that the x-axis is the 2-eigenspace of B, and the y-axis is the -1-eigenspace of B; likewise, the v_1-axis is the 2-eigenspace of A, and the v_2-axis is the -1-eigenspace of A.  This is consistent with the , as multiplication by C changes e_1 into Ce_1 = v_1 and e_2 into Ce_2 = v_2.

